<DOC><DOCNO> AP880320-0030 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-88 1148EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Nigeria-AIDS     03-20 0125</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Nigeria-AIDS,0128</SECOND><HEAD>Callers Swamp Nigerian AIDS Hotline</HEAD><DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A 24-hour telephone line set up to fieldquestions about AIDS has been averaging 100 calls daily in itsfirst week of operation, a newspaper reported Sunday.   Most callers want to know how the virus can be transmitted andways to prevent it, Dr. Doyin Odupe, president of the NigeriaCouncil on AIDS Education, which runs the national hot line, wasquoted in the Lagos Concord newspaper as saying.   Nigeria, with an estimated 100 million people, has only 20 knowncases of acquired immune deficiency syndrome.   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles orsyringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,and from pregnant women to their offspring.</TEXT></DOC>